  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "Is 2Mbps a good speed for browsing and downloading limited things over broadband? Should I choose 4Mbps?",
  "response": "When deciding on a broadband speed, it's important to consider your specific needs and usage patterns.\n\n**Browsing:**\n- **2Mbps:** Generally sufficient for basic web browsing, checking emails, social media, and streaming music. Web pages will load reasonably well, but high-resolution images and videos may take a bit longer.\n- **4Mbps:** Offers a better browsing experience with quicker page loads, smoother social media usage, and better overall performance for standard online activities.\n\n**Downloading:**\n- **2Mbps:** Acceptable for downloading small files and software updates, but larger downloads will be quite slow.\n- **4Mbps:** More efficient for downloading files and applications, resulting in shorter wait times.\n\n**Streaming:**\n- **2Mbps:** Might be challenging for high-definition (HD) streaming. Standard-definition (SD) content should be manageable.\n- **4Mbps:** Better suited for HD streaming, offering fewer buffering issues and smoother playback.\n\n**Video Calls:**\n- **2Mbps:** Can work for standard video calls but may experience some quality issues.\n- **4Mbps:** Provides a more reliable and clearer video call experience.\n\n**Multiple Users:**\n- **2Mbps:** May struggle if multiple users or devices are connected and active simultaneously.\n- **4Mbps:** Better handles multiple users, though heavy concurrent usage might still slow things down.\n\n**General Recommendation:**\n- If your usage is mostly light browsing, email, and social media with occasional downloads, 2Mbps can suffice.\n- If you want a more seamless and faster experience, particularly for streaming, video calls, and downloads, choosing 4Mbps is advisable.\n\nUltimately, opting for a higher speed like 4Mbps generally provides a more comfortable and efficient Internet experience.",
